Description: Wait for asynchronous session tests to finish before comparison
 The TAP driver starts two psql sessions in the background. Session one sleeps
 for a total of thirteen seconds, but the driver waits only seven seconds after
 the foreground session returns. Depending on scheduling, the output file is
 compared while psql is still running. Use a conservative wait that covers the
 complete scripted session and removes the observed PG16 race.
Author: Pigsty Packaging Team <rh@vonng.com>
Forwarded: no
Last-Update: 2026-07-11

--- a/t/03_sessions.t
+++ b/t/03_sessions.t
@@ -15,7 +15,7 @@
 $ret = `psql -X -d regress_dbms_lock -f test/sql/session3.sql > results/session3.out 2>&1`;
 ok( $? == 0, "test for session3 lock");
 
-sleep(7);
+sleep(15);
 
 $ret = `psql -X -d regress_dbms_lock -c "SELECT action, session, (date_trunc('second', executed) - lag(date_trunc('second', executed)) over(PARTITION BY session)) FROM lock_test" > results/session.out`;
 ok( $? == 0, "result for sessions 2 and 3 work");
